<p>Chicago's cold climate demands robust HVAC systems capable of handling temperature extremes from sub-zero winters to humid summers reaching the 80s and 90s. For heating, high-efficiency natural gas furnaces with AFUE ratings of 90% or higher are most popular, though heat pumps are becoming viable options with newer cold-climate technology. Air conditioning systems should have SEER ratings of at least 16 for optimal efficiency during Chicago's humid summers, with many homeowners opting for variable-speed systems that provide better humidity control.</p>

<p>Ductless mini-split systems are increasingly popular in Chicago for their efficiency and zone control capabilities, particularly in older homes with radiator heating. These systems typically achieve SEER ratings of 20+ and HSPF ratings above 10, making them excellent complements to solar panel systems. For the average 1,650 square foot Chicago home, a 2.5-3 ton central air system or multiple mini-split zones totaling similar capacity provides adequate cooling, while heating requirements often demand 80,000-100,000 BTU furnaces depending on insulation quality and home age.</p>

